<HL> Who's News:
Again, Burr and Lorenzo Part Company
As People's Founder Leaves Texas Air
---
By Paulette Thomas
Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal</HL>
<DD> 04/13/87</DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO>
<IN> WNEWS TEX
AIRLINES (AIR) </IN>
<DATELINE> HOUSTON  </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The last time Donald C. Burr parted company with Texas Air Corp.'s Frank Lorenzo, he had big plans. 
He left in 1980 to build an innovative new airline from scratch: People Express. 

   Now, only a few months after Texas Air acquired People Express, Mr. Burr will be leaving Mr. Lorenzo's employ again. 
Mr. Burr, 45 years old, resigned effective this week as executive vice president of Texas Air, a post he had held only two months. 
But this time, his plans after Texas Air are far less ambitious. 
"Right now is a good time to just look around," he says. 

   There has been speculation about Mr. Burr's departure ever since Texas Air's acquisition of People Express reunited Mr. Burr with Mr. Lorenzo, his former low-fare competitor. 
Mr. Burr said that his dealings with the Texas Air chairman and chief executive officer were cordial, but he declined to be specific about his reasons for leaving. 
"I know -- surprise, surprise," Mr. Burr said in an interview. 
"But this was a mutually agreed-upon deal. 
We'll have to let people speculate about why." 

   The ups and downs of their past association were more conspicuous. 
In the days when the pair worked closely at Texas International, the predecessor of Texas Air, Mr. Burr was best man at Mr. Lorenzo's wedding. 
After Mr. Burr left to start up People Express with another Texas International alumnus, Gerald Gitner, the two airlines competed in several markets, and both made a run at Frontier Airlines last year. 
Mr. Burr won that round, but only to see his faltering empire bought at a cut-rate price by Mr. Lorenzo, several months later. 

   Mr. Burr's new role at Texas Air was never outwardly apparent. 
He was named executive vice president of Texas Air in February, and a board member of Continental Airlines, a unit of Texas Air. 
But his name was notably absent from a list of top management in company stock prospectuses last month. 
Even stranger was the sale of stock of Jet Capital Corp. to Mr. Burr -- which many took as a clue that he was among the tight circle of executives who run Texas Air. 
Jet Capital, a financial holding company controlled by Mr. Lorenzo, holds a class of Texas Air stock that controls appointments to three-quarters of the Texas Air board. 

   Mr. Burr claims there were never plans for him at Texas Air in the long term. 
He said the Jet Capital stock sale was part of his "incentive package" negotiated last fall. 
He received no severance package, and even laughed at the idea. 
"No golden parachute," he said. 
Mr. Burr said he has paid about $125,000, a one-quarter down payment on the Jet Capital stock, and isn't certain whether he will keep the stock. 

   Now that the operations of People Express have been merged into those of Continental, he said it was the proper time to leave. 
The poor service in the initial combined operations lived up to People Express's old nickname: "People Distress." 
The combined People and Continental operations resembled People's final days -- mountains of lost bags and dozens of canceled flights, but Texas Air says they have improved greatly since. 

   "I don't feel like we did as good as we could have, but it could have been a . . . lot worse," Mr. Burr said. 
He said he is satisfied because no People Express employees lost jobs in the merger, though many incurred financial losses after borrowing from People Express to buy People Express stock. 

   He won't discuss his plans, beyond writing a book about his experiences at People Express, the cult-like company in which all employees were "managers," and to whom Mr. Burr would often give inspirational speeches via video screens. 
"There was some powerful learning in those strong early years," he said, "and I learned from the mistakes in the later years." 

   He hinted that perhaps that experience won't be for naught. 
"Some people are saying there's only going to be six major airlines," he said. 
"I certainly don't think it's going to be the case. 
We'll have to wait and see." 

</TEXT>
