<CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: Huey Newton; ... Cops' longtime nemesis  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  PAST; BLACK; LEADER; MURDER; TRIAL; CLOSING; ANALYSIS  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  Police and prosecutors' "dream" would have been to see longtime Black Panther
nemesis Huey Newton stoop so low as to be killed while trying to rip off a
crack cocaine dealer, but that's not the way it happened, the man prosecuting
Newton's alleged murderer told jurors Tuesday.;   In a fiery second day of
closing arguments in the trial of Tyrone Robinson, Alameda County Deputy
District Attorney Ken Burr lashed out at insinuations by Robinson's attorney
that police were engaged in a "great, big conspiracy" to frame Robinson for
murder.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Local  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  'CONSPIRACY' ASSAILED AT NEWTON TRIAL
FIERY ARGUMENTS ARE PRESENTED AT ROBINSON TRIAL  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     "It's ironic because 20 years ago, that's the defense Huey P. Newton used"
when he beat charges that he murdered Oakland police officer John Frey, Burr
said.;   Defense attorney Alfons Wagner accused Oakland police and prosecutors
of "fast and loose playing with witnesses" who escaped criminal charges
themselves while giving investigators statements that Robinson murdered Newton
on a West Oakland street to gain status in the Black Guerrilla Family prison
gang.;   Robinson, 27, an admitted crack dealer who has spent most of his
adult life behind bars, contends he shot Newton three times after Newton fired
at him first.;   Wagner said authorities are seeking a murder conviction
rather than believing Robinson's self defense claim because they don't want
the public to think they are being lenient toward the man responsible for
their nemesis' death.;   In this case, authorities "kiss off anything (pending
against witnesses) because the prosecution was going to look good in the
prosecution of the guy who killed Huey Newton in this town of Oakland," Wagner
told the jury.;   But prosecutor Burr responded that the conspiracy theory was
fanciful and he told the jury he personally resented it.;   "It implies I am
doing something improper, and illegal, and immoral," Burr said.;   Wagner
contends that the prosecution's key witness, Brian Keith Walton, lied in
stating he saw Robinson shoot Newton first while Newton's hands were in the
air and then twice more through the head as he lay on the ground. Walton, a
friend of Robinson's who died last year in an apparently unrelated drug-house
shooting, was facing an auto theft charge at the time he gave his taped
statement to investigators.;   During the trial, Wagner also presented a
string of witnesses to talk about violent incidents in Newton's past,
including the killing of Frey -- in which a manslaughter conviction against
Newton was overturned -- and two other killings in which Newton was
implicated. The evidence was shown to demonstrate a lifelong propensity for
violence in support of Robinson's contention that Newton was armed, even
though police found no gun near Newton's body.;   Burr acknowledged that
Newton was a thorn in the side of local law enforcement for more than two
decades, a radical leader who "had a way of pulling law enforcement's chain, a
way of kind of rubbing law enforcement's noses in it." Most importantly, he
got away with Frey's murder, in the eyes of Frey's fellow Oakland police
officers.;   "What better epitaph could the Oakland Police Department write
than that . . . he's fallen so low he was killed trying to rip off a crack
dealer," Burr said. "That sings.";   But in defending the investigation, Burr
said, the evidence showed Robinson executed a defenseless Newton in the
"stupid" belief he'd "become somebody on the mean streets of West Oakland.";  
Burr is expected to complete his statements to the jury today.  </TEXT>
