<HEAD>Records: Businessman Led FBI To Bodies In 1964</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: DELETES extraneous 10th graf, `Warren said...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Mississippi businessman was the paid
informant who in 1964 led the FBI to the graves of three slain
civil rights workers, according to records of a defunct
segregationist state agency.
   Olen Burrage of Philadelphia, Miss., received $30,000 from the
FBI for this information,'' records from the Sovereignty Commission
show. The records quote their own informant.
   Burrage, however, denied that he had anything to do with the
killings.
   A federal judge last week ordered the records of the commission,
which tried to thwart civil rights groups in the 1950s and 1960s,
be opened to the public. The judge later stayed his ruling pending
an appeal.
   Portions of the records are included in the personal papers of
former Gov. Paul B. Johnson Jr. The complete records are in the
archives of the McCain Graduate Library at the University of
Southern Mississippi in Hattiesburg. Portions were made available
to The Clarion-Ledger in an agreement with the attorney general.
   Burrage told the newspaper Monday that he had nothing to do with
the killings of James Chaney, Andrew Goodman and Michael Schwerner.
He also denied that the FBI paid him for information.
   Burrage's attorney, Robert Thomas of Philadelphia, said his
client was tried on federal charges of conspiracy to violate the
civil rights of the three men in 1967 and acquitted.
   ``Hey, look, you can write whatever you want to,'' Burrage said
in a telephone interview with the Jackson Clarion-Ledger. ``I
didn't have nothing to do with it. I'm not going to have anything
to do with it now.
   ``I've been harassed for years and years on this mess. I don't
even want to talk to you about it,'' he said.
   Commission investigator A.L. Hopkins' search for the FBI
informant is contained in the commission's records. Hopkins is dead.
   Hopkins wrote a report on his investigation Aug. 6, 1964, two
days after the three bodies were found in a grave at the base of a
pond dam under construction on Burrage's land southwest of
Philadelphia.
   ``I have information from a confidential source ... that Mr.
Olen Burrage, a white male who owns the property where the bodies
were found, and who operates a truck line out of Philadelphia,
Mississippi, is the informant who directed the FBI to the spot,''
Hopkins said in the report.
   Joe Sullivan, who was the FBI agent in charge of the Neshoba
County investigation, said Monday that Burrage never received money
for information.
   ``I didn't pay any money to anybody,'' Sullivan said in an
interview from his New York City home. ``I certainly don't know
anything about it.''
   Sullivan said a freelance writer working on the case during the
44 days federal and state officials looked for the three had
offered a reward of $25,000 for information leading to the bodies.
   ``That was the genesis of all the talk up there,'' Sullivan
said. ``I think he was affluent enough he could have paid the
reward.
   The FBI file shows an informant led agents to the dam, but
Sullivan refused to identify the individual. ``I have never named
anybody, and I don't want to.''
   The commission was created by the Mississippi Legislature on
March 22, 1956, to preserve segregation in the state. The
commission became inactive in 1973 when then-Gov. Bill Waller
vetoed its funding. The Legislature abolished the commission and
ordered its files sealed for 50 years in 1977.
</TEXT>
