<HEADLINE>  CHARLES BURR, GARDEN WRITER  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     Mr. Burr was born in Los Angeles and attended public schools there. He
received a horticulture degree in 1927 from the University of California,
Davis, where during the 1920s he reported on sports for the university
newspaper.;    Mr. Burr worked for a nursery in Niles until 1936, when he
moved to Palo Alto. He moved to Portola Valley 15 years ago.;    After
inheriting the roof garden nursery at the Emporium store in San Francisco, he
was approached by an editor for the then San Francisco News, which was located
in the same block. The editor's offer was that Mr. Burr write a weekly garden
column in exchange for a byline containing the name of his business.;    After
Mr. Burr submitted about 80 garden articles, the News merged with the San
Francisco Call Bulletin, owned by William Randolph Hearst, and the garden
column continued, even after Mr. Burr closed his nursery.;    After he
submitted his 287th article, the San Francisco Examiner became an afternoon
newspaper and absorbed the News-Call Bulletin. Mr. Burr was not part of the
deal, so in 1973 he became the Mercury News garden columnist.;    When the
garden section was developed as a weekly special features section in 1976, Mr.
Burr became a contributing writer and later moved into the job of answering
questions submitted by readers.;    Mr. Burr's byline has appeared regularly
in professional publications such as Pacific Horticulture magazine and Pacific
Coast Nurserymen's magazine. He was a longtime member of the Peninsula chapter
of the California Association of Nurserymen and in January was elected an
honorary member of the Garden Writers Association of America.;    Mr. Burr is
survived by his wife of 53 years, Paula, of Portola Valley; a daughter, Jane
Zones of San Francisco; a son, Benjamin Burr of New York; and two grandsons,
Milo Sprague of New York and Isaac Zones of San Francisco.;    No service will
be held. Mr. Burr's cremated remains will be scattered at sea. The family
suggests donations to Strybing Arboretum, 9th Avenue at Lincoln Way, San
Francisco 94122.  </TEXT>
