<DESCRIPT>  PAST; BLACK; LEADER; MURDER; TRIAL; OAKLAND; CLOSING  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  Amid all the testimony about Huey P. Newton's violent past, the man accused of
murdering the Black Panther Party leader has "become a forgotten man" at his
own trial, a prosecutor reminded jurors Tuesday.;   Urging the jury to focus
on Tyrone Robinson and find the admitted petty drug dealer guilty of murder,
Alameda County Deputy District Attorney Ken Burr said Robinson's claim of self
defense "does not make sense" given the pattern of three bullet wounds to
Newton's head, delivered "as you would to execute somebody."  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Local  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  NEWTON KILLING TRIAL NEARS END
ATTORNEYS PRESENT CLOSING ARGUMENTS  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Shorter version ran on page 8B of the Morning Final edition  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     'Looking for a way out'; In his closing argument, Burr said Robinson, 27,
is not the bespectacled "yuppie" he appears to be sitting at the defense table
but "an impatient, violent man," tired of the hard life of prison and West
Oakland streets and looking for a way to break out.;   The means to that end
was through killing Newton, a crack-using "has-been" hero of Oakland's black
community who used to get drugs simply by declaring "I'm Huey P. Newton," Burr
said. To Robinson, killing Newton was a way to gain notoriety in the Black
Guerrilla Family, a prison-based gang, and become a decision maker in its drug
sales network, Burr said.;   Says Newton shot first; Robinson has testified
that he shot Newton in the pre-dawn hours on Aug. 22, 1989 after Newton fired
at him first. No gun was found near Newton's body, and Burr contended Robinson
concocted that story as well as a string of run-ins he'd allegedly had with
Newton over the years. Although Robinson said several people witnessed those
past encounters, he couldn't produce any of them to corroborate his story on
the witness stand.;   "He's making them up as he goes along," Burr said.;  
Other than his own testimony, much of Robinson's defense consisted of
statements of law enforcement officials and others regarding violent incidents
in Newton's past in an attempt to lend credibility to the notion Newton was
armed and ready to kill. Jurors heard about Newton's links to three deaths and
four assaults, although only one assault conviction ever was upheld against
him.;   Key witness attacked; In his own closing argument, Robinson's
attorney, Alfons Wagner, attacked the credibility of the prosecution's key
witness, a Robinson friend who testified at a 1989 preliminary hearing but who
was killed last year in a drug shooting police said was unrelated to the
Newton case.;   That witness, Brian Keith Walton, gave investigators taped
statements in which he said he saw Robinson fire the final two shots into
Newton's head as he lay defenseless on the ground. Walton also said Newton was
unarmed and that Robinson told him he killed Newton to earn status in the
Black Guerrilla Family.;   Walton granted immunity; But Wagner said Walton had
much to gain by telling police investigators -- under pressure to find someone
to prosecute for Newton's murder -- a story they wanted to hear. Prosecutors
dropped a pending automobile theft case against Walton and also granted him
immunity from possible charges as an accessory to Newton's killing because he
hid the gun Robinson used.;   "There's been some fast and loose playing with
witnesses in this case," Wagner said. Wagner said county law enforcement
officials, after unsuccessfully pursuing Newton on criminal charges for years,
didn't want to be accused "of letting this one slide by.";   Closing arguments
continue today.  </TEXT>
