<HEAD>Five Charged with Killing More Than 40 Wild Horses</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM GARDNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five ranch workers were charged Wednesday in
the slayings of more than 40 wild horses and burros, in a continuing
federal investigation into the killings of at least 10 times that
many animals.
   The workers are charged with violating the Wild and Free Roaming
Horse and Burro Act, a misdemeanor punishable by one year in prison
and a fine of $2,000, said Assistant U.S. Attorney Will Mattly.
   A federal grand jury returned indictments Tuesday naming David
Morehead and Shannon Brennan of Lovelock, Eugene John Thacker of
Winnemucca and David Thacker and Ronald Emory Hage of Cosgrave,
Mattly said.
   The indictments were handed up Tuesday, sealed under a judge's
order so the defendants would not know they had been charged until
they were in custody.
   Mattly He said all but Hage were in custody and Hage was expected
to surrender. The four in custody were held under $50,000 bail.
   Morehead is charged with seven counts of killing a wild horse or
burro from May 15 through June 1988 and one count of selling a
mustang and a burro to a livestock yard last February.
   He and Brennan are charged in two other counts with killing 28
wild horses and two wild colts in November 1987; Eugene and David
Thacker and Hage face five counts each for killing five wild horses
in August 1987.
   Mattly said the killings were in Lander and Pershing counties,
where more than 500 mustangs have been found dead since last August.
Most of the animals had been shot.
   Mattly gave no motives for the killings and would not say how the
five men were tracked down except to credit ``an extensive
investigation on the part of the Bureau of Land Management law
enforcement staff.''
   Bureau spokesman Bob Stewart said agents ``have very heavily
investigated since it was first brought to our attention last
August. We have interviewed over 200 people and done extensive
on-ground investigation.''
   Maxine Shane, public affairs specialist with the BLM, said the
bureau considered the case to be far from ended.
</TEXT>
