<DESCRIPT>  CAMPBELL; MAYOR; BEGIN; CITY; DEVELOPMENT; PLANNING  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  The continuing redevelopment of downtown Campbell, the search for an
acceptable use for the former Winchester Drive-in site, and the establishment
of fire protection service priorities are key issues that will command the
attention of new Mayor Donald R. Burr in the coming year.;   "There are a lot
of issues, but no big problems that I'm aware of," said Burr, Campbell's
police chief for 17 years until his retirement in 1987. "Like all cities,
Campbell is stressed financially and we have to be very select about how we
invest our money."  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  West Extra  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  NEW MAYOR ASSESSES ISSUES IN CAMPBELL  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     Of paramount importance, Burr said, will be how the city spends money from
the sale of bonds through the Campbell Redevelopment Agency.;   The city
council has already approved residential development in the downtown intended
not only to provide needed housing, but also to create a population to support
downtown businesses. Burr said the city now needs to attract other developers
to complete the redevelopment master plan.;   The downtown beautification
project, including the return of two-way traffic on East Campbell Avenue, is
set to begin early next year and is an important element in the redevelopment
effort.;   Burr added that while downtown redevelopment is important, the
council is aware "there are other areas in the city that we can't ignore.";  
A top priority for the council will be determining Campbell's future fire
protection needs. The council has ordered a fire protection services master
plan to be completed next year. One of the options to be studied is the
consolidation of the Campbell Fire Department with the county's Central Fire
Protection District, for greater efficiency. Burr said he would support
consolidation if the study overwhelmingly recommends it. "I'm open-minded and
I will rely on the study.";   The mayor also said he favors commercial
development of the Winchester Drive-in site, the largest remaining piece of
undeveloped land in the city. But he also said the recent decision by city
staff to withdraw a development application for the site, in the face of
opposition from many residents and businesses concerned about traffic, was
correct because the issue will require a lot more study.;   Burr, 57, vowed
communication will be the theme of his mayoral tenure and that he will make
himself available to all segments of the community. "People are going to have
questions and I'll be available to talk to any of them," he said.;   Burr
joined the Campbell Police Department in 1956 and served for 31 years, rising
through the ranks from patrolman to chief.;   He won his council seat in 1988,
after the death of longtime Councilman Ralph P. Doetsch Sr.;   Each November,
Campbell's five council members choose a new mayor and vice mayor. Along with
Burr last week, Barbara D. Conant, a teacher at Monroe Middle School in the
Campbell Union School District, was elected vice mayor. Conant is the second
woman in city history to win that post.  </TEXT>
