<DESCRIPT>  OAKLAND; TRIAL; PAST; BLACK; CIVIL; RIGHT; LEADER; MURDER  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  Huey P. Newton always beat the most serious criminal charges brought against
him, but there was no one to rise to his defense Monday when jurors heard from
witnesses to the two killings he was accused of committing in 1967 and 1974.; 
 As the posthumous trial of Huey Newton continued in the case of the man
accused of murdering him, a prosecutor who spent a good portion of his career
trying to put Newton behind bars also testified that Newton "had gotten away
with what was a very serious crime against society" by avoiding prison in the
1967 killing of Oakland police officer John Frey.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Local  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  RETIRED COP AND EX-PROSTITUTE REMEMBER NEWTON, THE
KILLER  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     The defense attorney for Tyrone Robinson, 27, a drug dealer who admitted
shooting Newton on a West Oakland street corner Aug. 22, 1989, is putting
Newton's life on trial to show the late Black Panther Party leader was a
violent man capable of shooting at Robinson first, as Robinson contends. The
prosecution contends Newton was unarmed and Robinson "executed" him.;  
Retired Oakland police officer Herbert Heanes testified about the October 1967
shooting in which both he and Frey were shot in an altercation with Newton.
Newton was convicted of voluntary manslaughter, but the verdict was later
overturned on appeal and two attempts to retry Newton ended in mistrials.
Newton contended he fired in self-defense.;   Also testifying Monday was
Raphaelle Square, a former prostitute who said she was with Kathleen Smith the
night in August 1974 she was shot and killed on San Pablo Avenue.;   Square,
who was then known as Crystal Grey, said she saw Newton get out of a Lincoln
Mark IV and pull out a gun. After running away and returning, she said, she
heard a gunshot and saw Newton "standing over" Smith and "laughing at me" as
Square tried to reach her fallen friend.;   Newton fled to Cuba after Smith
was killed, but he returned to face the murder charge in 1977. Two trials in
the case ended in hung juries after Newton denied being at the scene.;   Tom
Orloff, who prosecuted Newton in the Smith case and now is Alameda County's
second-ranking prosecutor, testified that Newton "on occasion . . . was a very
violent person.";   Ken Burr, the deputy district attorney prosecuting
Robinson, did not cross-examine either Square or Heanes.;   From his boss,
Orloff, Burr elicited testimony that an Oakland journalist who testified last
week that Newton once admitted killing Smith never took that information to
authorities. Burr is attempting to discredit the journalist's testimony, even
though Orloff and other fellow prosecutors believe Newton committed the
crime.;   At a hearing with the jury out of the courtroom last week, Superior
Court Judge Alfred A. Delucchi expressed his concern that all the testimony
about Newton's past amounted to "trashing the victim" in order to give the
jury the impression that Newton "was such a bad guy he deserved to die.";  
But Burr said the defense had a right to present such evidence and did not
object to the testimony being presented. The defense expects to rest its case
today.  </TEXT>
