<DESCRIPT>  TRIAL; BEGIN; OAKLAND; MURDER; PAST; BLACK; POLITICS; LEADER  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  The final chapter in the life of Huey P. Newton began Monday as arguments over
whether he was a gun-toting cocaine thief or simply a fallen hero who paid the
ultimate price of his fame opened in the trial of his alleged killer.;   "You
can kill my body but you can't kill my soul. My spirit will live on forever,"
Alameda County prosecutor Ken Burr quoted the late Black Panther leader as
saying -- based on a witness account -- moments before Tyrone Robinson shot
him three times in the head on a dark West Oakland sidewalk Aug. 22, 1989.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Local  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  LAYING IT OUT FOR JURORS
NEWTON'S ALLEGED SLAYER GOES ON TRIAL
PROSECUTOR QUOTES SOME OF PANTHER'S LAST WORDS  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Shorter version ran P. 2B Morning Final Edition  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Robinson's attorney, Alfons Wagner, said his client will not deny shooting
Newton but will testify he did it after Newton fired a shot at him. No gun was
found near Newton.;   The first-degree murder trial promises, in part, to
relive the days of Newton and the Black Panthers, as Wagner said he will
support his defense by showing that Newton had a history of violence.;  
"Whatever else Huey Newton might have been, he was a violent, violent man,"
Wagner told the six-man, six-woman jury.;   The audience at opening statements
in the trial Monday in Alameda County Superior Court included former Black
Panther Party leaders David Hilliard and John Seale, and Newton's widow,
Fredrika.;   Hilliard, the party's former chief of staff, said outside the
courtroom that he found it "pretty strange" to hear an Alameda County district
attorney's representative run through the litany of community programs the
party sponsored after that same prosecutor's office spent years trying to put
Newton and other party members behind bars.;   He also said he didn't know
Newton, who once walked into the state Capitol with a rifle, to carry a gun in
the 1980s.;   "We put down the guns for three-piece suits and briefcases a
long time ago," Hilliard said.;   The prosecution and defense agree that
Newton, 47, was "tweaked," or high, on crack cocaine and looking for more
drugs on the morning he died. And both sides agree that Robinson, 27, was a
petty cocaine seller on the streets of West Oakland.;   Prosecutor Burr argued
that Robinson "executed" Newton, shooting him once in the jaw and twice
through the brain at close range as he lay on the ground, to gain prominence
in the Black Guerrilla Family prison gang.;   Robinson "wanted to be somebody
in the mean streets of West Oakland, and Huey Newton's death provided him with
that ticket," Burr said.;   Moments before shooting Newton, Robinson told a
friend on the street, "I'm going to kill (Newton), gonna get me some stripes,"
Burr said. And shortly after the shooting, according to the prosecutor,
Robinson boasted to other friends that "I'm going to be in control and you
guys are going to have to do what I tell you because I'm going to be
controlling the streets.";   Robinson's version, which he will give as the
first defense witness, will be substantially different, Wagner promised.;  
Robinson will talk about his recollections as a child of Black Panther
Party-sponsored breakfasts, of an uncle who helped deliver clothing for the
party, and how his parents told him "about Huey Newton killing a cop" -- a
charge on which Newton was convicted but which was later overturned.;  
Robinson also will say he had several run-ins with Newton before the shooting,
Wagner said, including one in which Newton shot at him as Robinson passed in a
car, and another confrontation in which Newton "took off" Robinson by stealing
crack cocaine from him at gunpoint.;   Although police never found a gun at
the scene, Wagner said there was gunshot residue evidence on Newton's arms,
indicating he had recently fired a weapon.;   In addition to their perceptions
of Huey Newton, jurors will have to consider the credibility of another dead
man -- Brian Walton, the only witness to the shooting. Walton, an associate of
both Newton's and Robinson's, died last year but left behind a series of
conflicting statements about what he saw. Much of the prosecution's case is
built around Walton's taped statements, which he seemed to recant at times and
support at times at a preliminary hearing in 1989.  </TEXT>
