<HEAD>Striking UAW Local Rejects Chrysler Contract For Second Time</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FENTON, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Striking United Auto Workers at a Chrysler
Corp. assembly plant on Wednesday narrowly rejected a new contract,
a week after walking off their jobs, a union official said.
   George Burr, president of UAW Local 110, said the three-year
agreement was rejected by 41 votes, with 1,197 members voting
against it and 1,156 voting for it.
   The suburban St. Louis plant is the only one producing the
long-wheelbase minivan, said Chrysler spokesman Lloyd Northard.
   It was the second vote on the contract, which was worked out
last Friday, two days after some 3,200 union members walked off
their jobs when negotiators failed to meet a contract deadline.
   In a vote Sunday, the contract was rejected by 61 percent of the
union's rank-and-file amid reports of illegal balloting.
   Burr said he thought the contract was rejected Wednesday because
of union members' concerns about outside contracting and
``outsourcing,'' the practice of shipping out work from the plant
to lower-paid workers.
   Those issues were taken away from Local 110 bargainers by the
international UAW, Burr said.
   The vote ``sends a message that the primary concern of the
people on the line and in the plant lies in the outsourcing and
outside contracting arena,'' Burr said. ``We recognize that this is
a problem.''
   Burr said the local leadership would be meeting Thursday and
would be in contact with the union's national leadership.
   Anthony P. St. John, vice president for human resources at
Chrysler Motors, said the company was ``deeply disappointed'' by
the vote because the local union bargaining committee, as well as
UAW Region 5 and the international union, had approved the
agreement last Friday.
   ``The result is that the St. Louis plant employees continue to
lose wages, several hundred employees elsewhere at Chrysler will
remain on layoff, and the corporate-wide profit sharing program for
all employees is affected adversely, as is Chrysler's loss of
revenue resulting from the strike,'' St. John said.
   ``We are considering the options available to us in this no-win
situation,'' he said.
</TEXT>
