<LEADPARA>  In an unusual alliance between prosecution and defense, attorneys in the trial
of Huey P. Newton's alleged murderer persuaded a judge Tuesday to allow jurors
to hear details about the numerous times the late Black Panther Party leader
was arrested for violent acts.;   Alfons Wagner, the attorney for defendant
Tyrone Robinson, will be able to put on the stand high-ranking law enforcement
officials and others who witnessed Newton's activities, arrested him or
prosecuted him.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Local  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  RARE ALLIANCE IN NEWTON TRIAL
ATTORNEYS WANT JURY TO HEAR OF SLAIN BLACK
PANTHER'S ARRESTS  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     The testimony will be part of Robinson's efforts to convince jurors that
Newton fired first when Robinson killed him on a West Oakland street Aug. 22,
1989. No gun was found near Newton, and Deputy District Attorney Ken Burr
contends Robinson "executed" Newton.;   Burr, whose colleagues long sought to
put Newton behind bars but were often frustrated in those attempts, agreed
that testimony about Newton's past is fair game. With the jury out of the
courtroom, Burr even persuaded Judge Alfred A. Delucchi to allow testimony
about Newton's 1964 conviction in a knife attack after the judge had said he
wouldn't allow it. It was the only conviction of Newton for a violent act that
was never overturned.;   "Yes, that type of stuff hurts (the prosecution
case)," Burr said, "but at the same time, (Wagner) has got a point.";   In
coming days, the jury will hear Alameda County Sheriff Charles Plummer talk
about arresting the then 16-year-old Newton in 1958 for hitting someone with a
hammer. Plummer was then a Berkeley police officer.;   Also now scheduled to
testify will be an officer who witnessed the 1967 shooting of an Oakland
police officer, a case that resulted in a manslaughter conviction for Newton
that later was overturned. And Tom Orloff, Alameda County's second-ranking
prosecutor who described Newton as a "gangster" after his death, will be
called to talk about Newton's reputation.;   In testimony Tuesday, jurors
heard from an Oakland man who described an all-night crack cocaine binge with
Newton before Newton was shot. Willie Payne Jr. described how Newton would run
out of crack, head to the streets and show up again with another collection of
"rocks" to smoke.;   He also testified that Newton said he was going to "take
some dope" -- meaning steal -- from Robinson when he headed out of Payne's
house near the shooting scene for the last time.;   Payne said he didn't see
whether Newton had a gun, but Newton had talked about killing people who were
rumored to be looking for him for allegedly ripping off drug dealers.  </TEXT>
